<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100585258875997></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100585258875997><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=7023&mid=100585258875997>Damage Bonus</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=7023&mid=100585258875997#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=54553><span id= >rmpinney</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>5 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Nov 15th 2:29 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Something of note.  I see below a formula that calculates max damage by factoring in str, plus skill lvl, etc.  As a ranger, we get spells that do not increase str, but do increase our atk rating.  By increasing the attack rating, all else equal, the max damage does appear to go up.  One prime example is when I am in wolf form (about +35 to attack) and have Str of Nature buff on (another +25), I see my max hits go up from somewhere around 57 or 58 to about 66 or 67 (jagged blade of mourning).  Anyone have any insight on the true affect of increasing attack rating versus increasing str?<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
